A new girl came to the gym this month. She told me she had been doing 
kickboxing for a year, so I decided to tune up the sparring speed a bit, 
but I quickly found she couldn't take it. She was very frustrated and when 
I tried to explain to her that I'm just an average fighter and that I can't 
even compare to my upperclassmen who are fighting in pro Thai matches, she 
said she didn't believe me because I fought better than most people she had 
met. I had her tell me what kind of training did they do at her last gym, 
and she told me that they basically spent all the time just hitting each 
other like mindless animals because they believed that it would make them 
stronger. No proper technique at all, no shadow boxing, no hitting the 
mitts or the bag... 

So, yeah, McDojos are everywhere and they don't limit to one single 
discipline. I practise Karate as well and any kid from the junior class in 
my Dojo could take down this guys in a matter of seconds. When I started 
Muay Thai, having a proper background in Karate helped me pick up the 
techniques much faster and grow very quickly. It doesn't matter what you 
do, just find a proper teacher and a training group that's both serious and 
commited but also nice and friendly. People who get too cocky and enjoy 
picking on newcomers only slow down their own progress and the rest of the 
class as well.﻿
